<section xml:id="section-diagonalization-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl>

	<li>
	<title><term>similar matrices</term></title>
	<idx><h>similar matrices</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>similarity</h></idx>
	<p> a pair of square matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> for which there exists an invertible matrix <m>P</m> satisfying <m>B=\inv{P}AP</m> </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<!-- This is explored in similarity.d/activity.xml.
<note><p>
	Similarity is <term>symmetric</term>:
	if <m>B</m> is similar to <m>A</m> with <m>B = \inv{P}AP</m>,
	then <m>A</m> is similar to <m>B</m> by <m>A = \inv{Q}BQ</m>,
	for <m>Q = \inv{P}</m>.
</p></note>
-->

<p><dl>

	<li>
	<title><term>transition matrix</term></title>
	<idx><h>transition matrix</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>transition</h></idx>
	<p> an invertible matrix <m>P</m> that realizes a similarity relationship <m>B=\inv{P}AP</m> for similar matrices <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> </p>
	</li>

	<li>
	<title><term>diagonalizable</term></title>
	<idx><h>diagonalizable</h></idx>
	<idx><h>matrix</h><h>diagonalizable</h></idx>
	<p> a square matrix that is similar to a diagonal matrix </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<p>
The next two definitions apply to an eigenvalue of a square matrix.
<dl>

	<li xml:id="definition-diagonalization-alg-mult">
	<title><term>algebraic multiplicity</term></title>
	<idx><h>algebraic multiplicity</h></idx>
	<idx><h>multiplicity</h><h>algebraic</h></idx>
	<idx><h>eigenvalue</h><h>multiplicity</h><h>algebraic</h></idx>
	<p> the number of times the eigenvalue is repeated as a root of the characteristic polynomial of the matrix </p>
	</li>

	<li xml:id="definition-diagonalization-geom-mult">
	<title><term>geometric multiplicity</term></title>
	<idx><h>geometric multiplicity</h></idx>
	<idx><h>multiplicity</h><h>geometric</h></idx>
	<idx><h>eigenvalue</h><h>multiplicity</h><h>geometric</h></idx>
	<p> the dimension of the corresponding eigenspace </p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

</section>
